The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Thursday, April 15, 2004 				 Vajpayee peace hope
																								Jammu, April 14 (PTI): Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee today said peace between India and Pakistan should be permanent and hoped the ongoing dialogue process will continue and succeed.																								We want peace to be permanent. We are neighbours and we have to live together, he said at an election rally here that many villagers could not attend because of the massive security cover.																								Vajpayee noted that India had always maintained that all disputes should be resolved through talks. We are happy that Pakistan has now accepted this and both nations are moving on the path of improving ties, he said.																								Without naming the All Parties Hurriyat Conference, Vajpayee regretted that they had refused to participate in the elections, though they talk about democracy.																								Vajpayee took a swipe at the Congress, saying they had been ruling the country for some time now and it was time for them to take rest.
